I think the easiest way here would be to define a fraction type, something like:

``` java
public final class Fraction {
   private final int numerator;
   private final int denominator;

   // expose with getters as needed
   private final boolean isWhole;
   private final boolean isTopHeavy;

   public Fraction(final int numerator, final int denominator) {
      this.numerator = numerator;
      this.denominator = denominator;
      isWhole = numerator == denominator;
      isTopHeavy = numerator &gt; denominator; 
   }

   // if your fractions are passed to you as Strings you can add a constructor that takes a string

   @override public toString() {
      // code to print appropriate message
      // using &quot;/&quot; and &quot;%&quot; may be helpful when building the string
   }
}

```

All the logic with how to translate the fraction to a string can go in the `toString` method (and helper methods as required)

You also give yourself a logical location to add additional functionality and operations to the `Fraction` if you need to in the future.

